1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,019
It's like the dumbest point in arguing about that.

2
00:00:09,922 --> 00:00:15,827
But this teaching about rebirthing, we should be able to experience it now.

3
00:00:16,189 --> 00:00:18,571
Everything of the Buddha is known as Dita down there.

4
00:00:18,591 --> 00:00:20,373
It's something to be seen here and now.

5
00:00:20,893 --> 00:00:23,216
It's not true here and now, it won't be true in the future.

6
00:00:23,676 --> 00:00:24,236
That's all.

7
00:00:24,257 --> 00:00:25,579
It's as simple as that.

8
00:00:25,599 --> 00:00:27,821
So let's just take the body.

9
00:00:28,121 --> 00:00:29,362
Is it reincarnating?

10
00:00:29,646 --> 00:00:30,829
or is it reverting?

11
00:00:31,268 --> 00:00:37,197
Reincarnation, the word suggests, is the same body arising moment after moment.

12
00:00:38,759 --> 00:00:45,527
Now, I think all of you know that every cell, every atom in the body is replaced every seven years.

13
00:00:45,747 --> 00:00:46,408
That's what they tell us.

14
00:00:47,670 --> 00:00:51,756
So tomorrow, when you look in the mirror, just remind yourself, this face wasn't here seven years ago.

15
00:00:52,106 --> 00:00:52,567
Okay?

16
00:00:53,529 --> 00:00:57,753
Now the fact is that every seven years the phase looks approximately the same.

17
00:00:57,874 --> 00:01:01,737
I mean, it is getting worse, but it looks approximately the same.

18
00:01:01,758 --> 00:01:05,141
So there's a feeling that it is the same phase, but we know it isn't.

19
00:01:05,882 --> 00:01:06,623
It's reverting.

20
00:01:06,963 --> 00:01:09,246
Every cell is reverting in its own way.

21
00:01:09,787 --> 00:01:10,168
Okay?

22
00:01:10,188 --> 00:01:10,789
Every atom.

23
00:01:11,310 --> 00:01:13,152
That's the process of rebirth.

24
00:01:13,171 --> 00:01:14,233
Think about your...

25
00:01:14,617 --> 00:01:17,221
your emotional life.

26
00:01:17,641 --> 00:01:24,368
And when we say the body, by the way, I'm here meaning also the sensations that come from the body, because the body gives us.

27
00:01:24,728 --> 00:01:29,733
So the sight of our eyes probably get a bit weaker as we get older and things like that.

28
00:01:30,034 --> 00:01:35,760
So even though the eyes are reverting, they're also getting worse, but that's the way it is.

29
00:01:35,781 --> 00:01:40,686
But every moment, every moment, you see, you can't say this is the same body as the last.

30
00:01:41,167 --> 00:01:42,447
And yet here it is.

31
00:01:42,816 --> 00:01:47,165
That gives us an idea of the distinction between reincarnation and rebirth.

32
00:01:48,808 --> 00:01:54,698
If we go into the mind, just consider your emotions, your emotional life.

33
00:01:55,019 --> 00:01:58,146
Sometimes peaceful, sometimes not so peaceful.

34
00:02:00,751 --> 00:02:01,972
It's constantly birthing, isn't it?

35
00:02:03,893 --> 00:02:27,122
there's constantly this process of emoting all the time all you have to do is just stop still and place your attention inward and there's some mood there, there's some emotion there but it's constantly changing there's this constant state of rebirthing re-arising into the present moment but it's never the same emotion what about thoughts?

36
00:02:28,843 --> 00:02:33,310
just think about how our thoughts have developed over the years say from the age of two

37
00:02:34,200 --> 00:02:35,522
It's changed, hasn't it?

38
00:02:35,543 --> 00:02:35,742
Hope.

39
00:02:37,225 --> 00:02:43,355
So you can see, we're still thinking, the thought we arrived at, but it's never the same thought.

40
00:02:46,199 --> 00:02:51,288
So now, when we die, well, let's see what happens.

41
00:02:51,307 --> 00:02:56,817
Now the Buddha points out, if we live according to our spiritual aspiration, if we live according

42
00:02:57,472 --> 00:03:06,682
according to goodwill, it generally, it will make our inner life more happy, more settled.

43
00:03:06,703 --> 00:03:11,889
I mean, if you're in a war situation, no matter how much goodwill you are, it's still not a pleasant place to be.

44
00:03:12,270 --> 00:03:18,918
But inwardly, you can begin to have a certain peacefulness about ourselves.

45
00:03:18,937 --> 00:03:23,544
And by doing that, we are forming relationships, so it helps the relationships around us.

46
00:03:25,246 --> 00:03:26,668
So, by practising peace,

47
00:03:26,968 --> 00:03:36,745
By developing spiritually, we're actually making this life, right here and now, something more pleasant for us, more happy, more meaningful.

48
00:03:38,548 --> 00:03:45,400
Now, according to the understanding, we're developing conditionings, these conditionings.

49
00:03:46,375 --> 00:03:59,455
So, if there is no rebirth after death, if we just annihilate, fine, but at least we've had a fairly decent life, I mean, we've been gentle, yeah?

50
00:03:59,474 --> 00:04:08,247
If we happen to rebirth and find ourselves in another place, another time, then these conditionings come with us.

51
00:04:08,937 --> 00:04:11,561
Because you don't arrive there with nothing.

52
00:04:12,181 --> 00:04:19,372
So these conditions come with us and then we'll be very happy that during the last life we did a bit of practice.

53
00:04:19,391 --> 00:04:20,653
So it's a win-win situation.

54
00:04:24,177 --> 00:04:26,601
I think.

55
00:04:28,124 --> 00:04:32,088
But these concerns about rebirth is... What's the point?

56
00:04:35,053 --> 00:04:36,074
Our...

57
00:04:36,814 --> 00:04:42,223
Our attention spiritually, see, from a spiritual point of view, is right here and now.

58
00:04:42,483 --> 00:04:44,024
It's the only moment we've got anyway.

59
00:04:44,927 --> 00:04:51,815
It's this, you know, the whole of our practice, the whole of our effort should be getting this moment right.

60
00:04:55,762 --> 00:04:59,127
There we are.

61
00:04:59,146 --> 00:05:02,031
You talked earlier about... Oh, there's any questions, rather?

62
00:05:02,091 --> 00:05:04,675
I'm sorry, I should... Any...

63
00:05:04,694 --> 00:05:06,416
Criticism?

64
00:05:06,952 --> 00:05:14,867
You talked earlier about the link between identification and the arising of suffering.

65
00:05:14,887 --> 00:05:20,338
Could you say a little bit more about identification as a phenomenon, as a process?

66
00:05:27,540 --> 00:05:40,675
Just for those of you who've been into Buddhist practice for some time, historically speaking, when the Buddha talks, he's very careful to talk about experience.

67
00:05:44,841 --> 00:05:48,564
He's very careful to keep his language mainly about experience.

68
00:05:48,584 --> 00:05:53,110
So when he talks about nirvana, he's talking about an experience.

69
00:05:57,646 --> 00:06:26,100
as Buddhism developed the action changed away from the experience to what is it that experiences the experience and that became what's known as the consciousness only school when we're practicing and we are pulling ourselves out of this body with its sensations when I say that I mean they become objects you can feel feelings

70
00:06:26,502 --> 00:06:54,432
when you pull out of your emotions you've found a position where you can feel emotions you're aware of your emotions all the time this awareness is beginning to disidentify with what it previously would have identified with and this backwards step you see leads to the realisation of what this awareness is

71
00:06:55,408 --> 00:07:01,779
And the word I prefer for that is the knowing, rather than consciousness, because these days that word's been used in all sorts of ways.

72
00:07:02,321 --> 00:07:13,982
The knowing is a rather good word in English, because it's one of these gerunds which has a verbal meaning, knowing, so it doesn't coagulate so much into some thing.

73
00:07:15,363 --> 00:07:15,865
So,

74
00:07:16,317 --> 00:07:29,685
this knowing has the capacity of being aware and it is our intuitive intelligence that's what it is and it's prior to thought

75
00:07:29,901 --> 00:07:58,642
thought isn't intelligence it's prior to thought, it uses thought to express its understanding it's prior to emotion it uses the emotional life to express its understanding and it's prior to the body it uses the body to express its understanding so these are three so-called intelligences our physical intelligence that we see in sport our emotional intelligence and our intellectual intelligence but these are simply expressions

76
00:07:59,264 --> 00:08:01,908
coming from this knowing.

77
00:08:01,927 --> 00:08:14,266
And this knowing becomes more apparent to us the more we distinguish between that which knows, the awareness, the looking, the observing, and what is actually experiencing.

78
00:08:16,970 --> 00:08:17,550
See?

79
00:08:17,571 --> 00:08:21,656
I forgot the question.

80
00:08:22,137 --> 00:08:22,538
Yes?

81
00:08:23,428 --> 00:08:28,254
It sounded like intuition to me, some kind of deep intuition, what you just talked about.

82
00:08:28,853 --> 00:08:38,823
I was down at the dinner table, and there was this pot of hummus, and I wanted to take something inside me and say, don't do it.

83
00:08:39,605 --> 00:08:42,167
And I thought, that's stupid, I really like hummus, why shouldn't I eat it?

84
00:08:42,847 --> 00:08:45,250
And it said, don't do it, and I thought, oh, bother.

85
00:08:45,691 --> 00:08:49,875
And I took my spoon and lifted it up, and the lady across the table

86
00:08:50,041 --> 00:08:54,246
reached over and I smacked the spoon again so I had it on hold for a moment.

87
00:08:54,888 --> 00:09:08,606
So I think I had some intuitive inkling, well I shouldn't do it but I didn't understand it and I didn't listen to it either and yeah, that's kind of stupid.

88
00:09:09,261 --> 00:09:38,457
I'm not sure I would take that as a great example what I would say is that there's a confusion between intuition and the feeling of intuition now you've got to be careful because this intelligence in Buddhist understanding is deluded so you may feel something is right but it's not necessarily so just as we may think something is right and it's not necessarily so everything that we feel and think has to be questioned

89
00:09:39,028 --> 00:09:41,812
Don't think that just because I have a feeling it must be right.

90
00:09:45,394 --> 00:09:55,365
Sometimes these feelings come in other ways, like voices from God, like that guy who went and swam across the lake to say Aung San Suu Kyi.

91
00:09:55,985 --> 00:09:59,889
So you have to be very careful about, you know, the intuitive feeling must be right.

92
00:10:00,230 --> 00:10:01,471
You have to question it too.

93
00:10:05,235 --> 00:10:05,695
Now,

94
00:10:07,361 --> 00:10:28,750
this process of stepping back out of the body with its sensations and so on is the process of disidentification you're redefining yourself I'm not the body I'm observing the body, I feel the body but I am not the body I'm not emotions, I feel them, I know them but I am not that, see?

95
00:10:28,770 --> 00:10:35,039
so you're constantly stepping out of previous identification and as I mentioned I think this morning

96
00:10:36,049 --> 00:11:05,922
the observer is the most difficult one to overcome because you can't step out of that if you step out of that you simply create another observer observing the observer it's a sort of endless mirror process so that is beyond our control that happens when the times are right so every time we

97
00:11:06,390 --> 00:11:11,035
fall into an identification, we become what we identify with.

98
00:11:12,636 --> 00:11:13,658
That's why it hurts.

99
00:11:13,697 --> 00:11:14,879
That's where the suffering is.

100
00:11:15,100 --> 00:11:22,726
So this pain in my knee, so long as I can observe it as pain, so I'm saying pain, pain, see?

101
00:11:23,788 --> 00:11:26,051
And there's this push away from it.

102
00:11:26,071 --> 00:11:26,191
Right?

103
00:11:27,932 --> 00:11:28,712
I don't want to, right?

104
00:11:29,033 --> 00:11:35,519
Now, in meditation, I'm observing this resistance not to be with the pain in an equanimous way, not to open up to it.

105
00:11:36,495 --> 00:11:43,485
And because of that, this begins, this reaction, it's only a reaction, begins to die away, and I find myself peaceful with pain.

106
00:11:45,126 --> 00:11:48,951
This is on the presumption that he is not about to explode.

107
00:11:49,091 --> 00:11:50,453
We're not trying to defeat pain.

108
00:11:52,056 --> 00:11:53,457
We're not trying to be better than pain.

109
00:11:53,979 --> 00:11:56,061
We're just trying to investigate what pain is.

110
00:11:56,402 --> 00:12:05,153
So now this resistance has gone, and I'm sitting just with this sort of ache in my knee, and I'm saying things like pain or aching, you see.

111
00:12:05,419 --> 00:12:11,890
Then, as it were, I drop into the pain, I drop into those sensations.

112
00:12:11,910 --> 00:12:18,301
And as I drop into it, deep into it, I actually begin to feel the sensations, my noting work changes.

113
00:12:19,082 --> 00:12:21,366
I begin to say things like heat or pressure.

114
00:12:23,409 --> 00:12:26,414
And at that point, you see, there's no suffering.

115
00:12:27,104 --> 00:12:32,791
Suddenly, as I move my awareness upwards, as it were, and it becomes pain again, then I get the resistance.

116
00:12:32,811 --> 00:12:35,533
Then I realise that pain is a mental construct.

117
00:12:35,553 --> 00:12:36,576
It doesn't actually exist.

118
00:12:37,115 --> 00:12:41,260
What exists are sensations coming from the knee.

119
00:12:41,280 --> 00:12:43,023
So these are your investigations.

120
00:12:43,102 --> 00:12:47,428
And so, in so doing, you disidentify with the idea of pain.

121
00:12:48,429 --> 00:12:51,394
And that helps you to find an equanimity with it.

122
00:12:52,654 --> 00:12:55,057
Now, as I say, you only do this to a certain point.

123
00:12:56,399 --> 00:12:56,740
That's that.

124
00:13:00,043 --> 00:13:04,828
So, every time we fall into an identification, suffering will come.

125
00:13:04,849 --> 00:13:08,392
Even in everyday life, as soon as you identify with your job, right?

126
00:13:08,812 --> 00:13:11,575
I am a nurse, you know, I am a whatever.

127
00:13:11,634 --> 00:13:16,019
As soon as I am something, there's potential of suffering.

128
00:13:16,039 --> 00:13:17,301
You lose your job, who are you?

129
00:13:17,701 --> 00:13:17,902
Yeah?

130
00:13:17,922 --> 00:13:19,763
You go through an identity crisis.

131
00:13:21,024 --> 00:13:21,225
See?

132
00:13:21,304 --> 00:13:26,950
Rather to say to yourself, this is what I do, rather than this is what I am.

133
00:13:26,990 --> 00:13:28,532
Yeah?

134
00:13:29,929 --> 00:13:36,720
And at the more subtle level, there's the relationship of possession.

135
00:13:39,244 --> 00:13:39,384
See?

136
00:13:39,403 --> 00:13:42,970
When you possess something, you possess people, you possess them.

137
00:13:43,330 --> 00:13:52,644
So that relationship is one where this object, or this person, is being held by you, clasped, grasped by you.

138
00:13:53,004 --> 00:13:56,190
So there there's tremendous potential for suffering.

139
00:13:56,794 --> 00:14:06,528
If the person goes, disappears, dies, whatever, then you're left with this burning ache in the heart, which is that grasping.

140
00:14:06,548 --> 00:14:08,150
If you lose something, you get very angry.

141
00:14:09,852 --> 00:14:11,395
If somebody takes it, you get even more angry.

142
00:14:13,558 --> 00:14:13,859
You know?

143
00:14:14,899 --> 00:14:24,413
And some of you will hear me say, if somebody steals something from you, you still go around saying, you know, they stole my car, they stole my purse.

144
00:14:25,836 --> 00:14:26,716
It's theirs.

145
00:14:27,541 --> 00:14:30,764
Of course.

146
00:14:31,304 --> 00:14:32,885
It's about the living in the delusion.

147
00:14:32,946 --> 00:14:35,269
That is yours.

148
00:14:35,408 --> 00:14:36,690
See?

149
00:14:36,710 --> 00:14:39,893
And as soon as you click onto that, then you see compassion arises.

150
00:14:39,913 --> 00:14:41,794
You say, well, they can have it.

151
00:14:41,815 --> 00:14:43,197
Just like that.

152
00:14:43,216 --> 00:14:51,164
You've got insurance anyway.

153
00:14:51,184 --> 00:14:51,904
Any questions?

154
00:14:52,986 --> 00:14:53,866
Any observations?

155
00:14:55,129 --> 00:14:55,489
Additions?

156
00:15:00,986 --> 00:15:04,331
You can only use objects, you can only do your work.

157
00:15:05,552 --> 00:15:09,197
As soon as you identify or possess, problems will arise.

158
00:15:09,238 --> 00:15:22,796
Can you talk a little about how to remain grounded in meditation and why this might be important?

159
00:15:23,116 --> 00:15:27,923
Well, I think I mentioned it again this morning,

160
00:15:28,628 --> 00:15:41,288
The process of insight, real insight, can only happen when this intuitive intelligence can completely pull itself out of, disidentify with thought.

161
00:15:42,208 --> 00:15:45,033
So thought here includes not only words but images.

162
00:15:45,975 --> 00:15:50,621
Words and images contain our history.

163
00:15:51,062 --> 00:15:53,246
They contain our past experience.

164
00:15:54,187 --> 00:15:56,711
And they are like coloured glasses

165
00:15:57,534 --> 00:16:23,965
that make us see present experience from the view of the past and therefore we're always in a state of comparison or contradiction even if it's a very subtle thing so you meet a friend and you expect them to be like this because of your past experience with your friend if they're not like this then you get upset

166
00:16:31,100 --> 00:16:59,503
when you have some food an apple or something we always take the apple and we're always eating all our history of apples every time you bite that apple it's in comparison with all past apples so it's either not sweet enough or it's just absolutely perfect this is the apple but actually to taste this apple as this apple is you have to get rid of all that now how do we

167
00:16:59,720 --> 00:17:24,984
bring this intelligence back to direct experience of things as they are to understand and see things as they really are, the Buddhist way so you have to bring that intelligence out of thought and you do that by grounding it in your physical feeling experience so if you want to taste the apple, put your attention on your tongue

168
00:17:27,428 --> 00:17:37,364
If you want to see a tree, keep looking at it until, as it were, you're absorbed into the tree, rather than just seeing it as another tree.

169
00:17:42,452 --> 00:17:44,596
So, in the meditation, that's what we're doing.

170
00:17:44,876 --> 00:17:50,465
We're constantly trying to unshackle, unconfuse.

171
00:17:51,154 --> 00:18:12,858
disentangle this intelligence from its identity with thought thought patterns ideas and these things are very subtle so in your breath when you're watching the breath for instance the rising and falling of the abdomen or at the nostrils wherever you're watching it you'll see there's first of all some idea of movement okay

172
00:18:13,311 --> 00:18:39,807
something coming in something coming out there's somewhere a picture in your mind of your of your nose or your abdomen and there's sensation okay now what there is is sensation the idea of it rising and falling and the picture of the of the nose or the of the abdomen are mental constructs okay so by drawing our attention into the breath of sensation

173
00:18:40,935 --> 00:19:09,963
this intelligence begins to let go of that and begins to see sensation as sensation and in this way it's clarifying itself unshackling itself from these thoughts and images as a direct experience now it's not as though we want to get rid of that capacity remember that after the Buddha was awakened

174
00:19:10,383 --> 00:19:14,165
I mean, he spent 40 years.

175
00:19:16,107 --> 00:19:16,887
Yeah, 40 years.

176
00:19:17,969 --> 00:19:24,275
Teaching, walking around, talking, all these miserable people.

177
00:19:24,295 --> 00:19:26,096
And walking up and down and being ordinary.

178
00:19:26,115 --> 00:19:28,377
He wasn't a schizophrenic or anything.

179
00:19:28,817 --> 00:19:34,722
He didn't become a sort of amorphous blob under a tree with a sign, I am fully awake.

180
00:19:36,125 --> 00:19:38,026
I mean, he's an ordinary human being.

181
00:19:38,046 --> 00:19:40,288
He's going around in contact, speaking.

182
00:19:40,791 --> 00:20:07,001
so we don't lose the capacity of thought we just want to gain the capacity of letting it go being able to be directly in contact with experiences as they are not as we think they are or would wish them to be and that's part of the liberation that comes with taxing the passive see

183
00:20:10,863 --> 00:20:12,345
So how do you ground yourself?

184
00:20:12,865 --> 00:20:26,067
You ground yourself in your physical felt experience.

185
00:20:26,086 --> 00:20:28,611
What's an emotion before you give it a name?

186
00:20:29,731 --> 00:20:37,263
That's what you want to find out.

187
00:20:37,284 --> 00:20:38,405
Yeah, any questions there?

188
00:20:44,680 --> 00:20:49,286
you talked about staying with the emotions in meditation is there a time for this in daily life?

189
00:20:51,608 --> 00:21:14,079
sometimes you might find a bit of space to stop just to stop and just as it were contact your present condition but if our awareness if our mindfulness is spacious just generally loose, easy

190
00:21:15,190 --> 00:21:20,276
then as you're talking to somebody, you can be aware of what's happening inside of you.

191
00:21:20,355 --> 00:21:24,279
You can even be aware of the breath on the periphery of your attention.

192
00:21:25,942 --> 00:21:28,365
If you concentrate too much, then you lose it, you see.

193
00:21:29,526 --> 00:21:38,055
But it's a case of feeling at ease and just relaxing into a present situation, you see.

194
00:21:38,075 --> 00:21:44,843
When you walk into a room, just stop for a minute and just receive the room, you see.

195
00:21:48,231 --> 00:22:14,424
when you're with somebody and they're speaking we tend to already be preparing our answer but if we just receive what they're saying and feel what they're saying that's a mode of openness, receiving there's always a little break while the thing switches and we have to respond, you see?

196
00:22:15,738 --> 00:22:29,134
In that way the person really feels that you're really listening to them, you see, rather than trying to defeat them in an argument or something.

197
00:22:29,153 --> 00:22:42,369
So keeping in contact with just our general feeling, you'll see, it gives you a greater sense of control over your life, rather than just be driven by emotional states.

198
00:22:43,970 --> 00:22:47,153
You might be talking to somebody and you got a bit irritated, you see.

199
00:22:47,933 --> 00:22:54,380
But before you walk towards somebody else, you just try and find a little space there to let it dry out a bit.

200
00:22:56,122 --> 00:23:00,405
And then turn with that goodwill, you see, open-heartedness towards the other person.

201
00:23:03,249 --> 00:23:06,412
And you'll find stopping, constantly telling yourself to stop.

202
00:23:06,432 --> 00:23:08,114
It's a really lovely, powerful little word.

203
00:23:08,413 --> 00:23:09,335
One of those four-letter words.

204
00:23:10,256 --> 00:23:10,576
Stop.

205
00:23:10,957 --> 00:23:11,057
Stop.

206
00:23:16,201 --> 00:23:34,584
good at it you just say stop and the next thing to be done so if you can create that little gap before you do anything you see the intention so at that point you can say to yourself should I be doing this or not?

207
00:23:34,604 --> 00:23:35,365
should I take the hoops?

208
00:23:42,074 --> 00:23:43,255
and

209
00:23:48,819 --> 00:24:02,297
Be careful of this ability that we have of generating further and further like a whirlwind of emotions throughout the day that by the end of the day you feel exhausted.

210
00:24:03,377 --> 00:24:09,065
And you do that again by just stopping and whatever's come up you just let it begin to drain away.

211
00:24:09,204 --> 00:24:13,089
You don't have to wait till it totally goes but begin to drain away.

212
00:24:13,323 --> 00:24:17,070
I think you'll find you reserve a lot of energy.

213
00:24:17,111 --> 00:24:20,077
We use a lot of energy in these emotional states.

214
00:24:30,961 --> 00:24:32,444
Anything else about that?

215
00:24:41,977 --> 00:24:44,740
I consider myself a reasonably happy person.

216
00:24:46,183 --> 00:24:52,614
Rewarding though it is, should I be concerned with the ethics of putting so much effort into being happier?

217
00:24:54,155 --> 00:25:07,076
The purpose of the practice isn't to be happy.

218
00:25:08,077 --> 00:25:09,519
I remember once

219
00:25:10,916 --> 00:25:17,423
when a teacher arrived, and somebody said to him, oh, I'm so happy to see you, Sido.

220
00:25:18,003 --> 00:25:21,086
And Sido said something in Burmese.

221
00:25:21,667 --> 00:25:24,510
And the translator didn't translate it.

222
00:25:26,333 --> 00:25:33,840
And later on, the person who said, I'm so happy to see you, Sido, went to the translator and said, well, you know, like, what did he say?

223
00:25:34,461 --> 00:25:35,321
And he said, well...

224
00:25:35,707 --> 00:25:37,190
He said, I'm not here to make you happy.

225
00:25:37,509 --> 00:25:43,119
I'm here to make you aware.

226
00:25:45,003 --> 00:25:47,047
So our purpose is not to be happy.

227
00:25:47,188 --> 00:25:48,971
Happy is a consequence of the practice.

228
00:25:49,892 --> 00:25:54,119
If you try to make happiness your aim, then you're into a struggle.

229
00:25:56,597 --> 00:25:58,240
Happiness is a consequence.

230
00:25:58,280 --> 00:25:59,502
Peace is a consequence.

231
00:25:59,522 --> 00:26:01,887
You can't peace a situation.

232
00:26:02,548 --> 00:26:06,576
The active ingredients are love, compassion, sympathetic joy.

233
00:26:13,769 --> 00:26:20,461
Yeah?

234
00:26:25,977 --> 00:26:26,458
Death.

235
00:26:29,122 --> 00:26:31,986
What is it that scares so many so much?

236
00:26:33,307 --> 00:26:34,409
Where is thy sting?

237
00:26:36,752 --> 00:26:40,759
Well, this goes back to our problem of identity.

238
00:26:42,020 --> 00:26:51,094
If I think I am this body, and it goes off, and it's going to die, then heck, I'm going to be afraid, aren't I?

239
00:26:51,114 --> 00:26:51,494
It's me.

240
00:26:52,896 --> 00:26:53,857
It's me that dies.

241
00:26:55,930 --> 00:27:01,516
So that identity has, at its deepest root, a real basic fear.

242
00:27:02,457 --> 00:27:10,144
And our problem is that we know we're not real, but we don't accept it.

243
00:27:12,606 --> 00:27:13,428
We know we're not real.

244
00:27:14,348 --> 00:27:16,230
You can walk out of here and that'd be the end of that.

245
00:27:16,692 --> 00:27:17,972
You might get knocked over by a car.

246
00:27:18,073 --> 00:27:18,834
Boom, boom, that's it.

247
00:27:19,213 --> 00:27:20,295
And what happens to your body?

248
00:27:21,096 --> 00:27:22,698
Stick in the box and off it goes.

249
00:27:24,279 --> 00:27:25,701
We know we're not real.

250
00:27:27,165 --> 00:27:28,307
But we insist we are.

251
00:27:30,130 --> 00:27:36,861
And our feeling of reality comes at its most painful when that reality is denied.

252
00:27:37,461 --> 00:27:39,545
And it's denied most obviously by our death.

253
00:27:42,189 --> 00:27:44,070
No wonder so many of us are so scared.

254
00:27:44,090 --> 00:27:44,271
I am.

255
00:27:48,317 --> 00:27:54,126
So that's what we're trying... You could say that the practice of vipassana is a preparation for a peaceful death.

256
00:27:55,268 --> 00:27:55,788
That's what you could say.

257
00:28:06,011 --> 00:28:34,467
one of these phrases you have to die before you die spiritually speaking that means die to this self before you die and Jesus put it another way slightly more joyfully you might say you have to be reborn so to be reborn something must have died

258
00:28:36,994 --> 00:28:38,958
Spiritually speaking, that's what it's talking about.

259
00:28:38,998 --> 00:28:44,586
It's not talking about jumping up and down for Jesus.

260
00:28:44,606 --> 00:28:45,067
Gardening.

261
00:28:45,689 --> 00:29:04,638
You mentioned joy being the way of love and a way of love and being akin to desire for gratification.

262
00:29:06,172 --> 00:29:15,185
the right way for true love of being can you explain please?

263
00:29:16,407 --> 00:29:32,854
with all these virtues that we have they have obviously what's known as in the commentarial literature an obvious enemy so the obvious enemy is love is hate but they always have a subtle enemy to it

264
00:29:33,424 --> 00:29:38,050
So love, as we've said, is attachment.

265
00:29:38,432 --> 00:29:41,115
That means that you want, you need something.

266
00:29:42,857 --> 00:29:46,482
Some of your happiness is dependent on something out there.

267
00:29:46,923 --> 00:29:49,086
That's what attached love is.

268
00:29:49,847 --> 00:29:52,511
In other words, you need to be loved.

269
00:29:52,771 --> 00:29:57,499
It's that sort of feeling.

270
00:29:58,519 --> 00:30:02,065
Loneliness is the need...

271
00:30:02,617 --> 00:30:07,204
For somebody to say they love you, or to express their love, you feel alone.

272
00:30:07,444 --> 00:30:08,906
You don't feel alone, you feel lonely.

273
00:30:09,929 --> 00:30:11,290
And they're not very nice feelings.

274
00:30:11,550 --> 00:30:16,038
In fact, in some cases, it can lead people to despair, even suicide.

275
00:30:18,161 --> 00:30:23,650
But the more you demand that people feed into this loneliness, paradoxically, the more lonely you feel.

276
00:30:24,270 --> 00:30:31,781
Because you know it's a demand, it's not coming from them, it's not natural, it's not given from their heart.

277
00:30:37,718 --> 00:30:39,661
So how do you deal with something like that?

278
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:48,933
You have to sit with the loneliness, feel it, get in touch with that feeling of not being worthy, self-hatred, whatever comes up with it.

279
00:30:48,953 --> 00:30:54,321
And as it begins to die away, you begin to see these little, little arisings.

280
00:30:54,422 --> 00:30:56,344
It's beginning to transform.

281
00:30:57,145 --> 00:30:58,607
And the transformation is what?

282
00:30:58,988 --> 00:31:01,332
From loneliness to what?

283
00:31:01,392 --> 00:31:01,912
There you go.

284
00:31:03,074 --> 00:31:03,615
Solitude.

285
00:31:05,136 --> 00:31:07,319
Solitude is being perfectly happy beings

286
00:31:07,537 --> 00:31:36,970
your own now if you're perfectly happy being on your own you can see that there's a lot of energy there to love somebody else and you don't expect them you don't need them to fill the hole within your own heart so whenever you find yourself in a position of loving or compassion and you can feel these subtle enemies like grief for somebody

287
00:31:37,355 --> 00:31:40,577
in compassion how does that help?

288
00:31:41,077 --> 00:32:04,019
grieving for somebody compassion should be a joyful emotion you are helping somebody sympathetic joy becomes excited so that it's feeding into your need to be happy all these are very subtle things that happen within us and we get confused and say well this is true love, this is true compassion

289
00:32:04,590 --> 00:32:13,961
But as you know, if I start doing things in order to be happy, going back to this other thing about I'm happy, why should I be more happy?

290
00:32:13,981 --> 00:32:21,891
If I start helping you so that I can be happy, then I get into this classic do-gooder position.

291
00:32:22,832 --> 00:32:31,662
And I define a do-gooder as a person who wants to do you the good they want to do you.

292
00:32:43,807 --> 00:33:10,355
so true love how do you how would you go about establishing true love it's always beginning from where the other person is you're trying to relate to this person so you know where you're coming from right and then you try and put yourself into their position and you do that by asking them what do they want there's a lovely scripture called the I can't remember what it's called now but the Buddha approaches these three

293
00:33:10,673 --> 00:33:37,136
Arahats they're fully liberated beings they're three monks who are living together and he asks them how do you live so peacefully together and Anaruda replies well I say to myself what if I put what I want to do aside and do what the others want to do and in this way we live peacefully now that really only works if you're the person saying the same

294
00:33:37,875 --> 00:34:07,056
you get to be used and abused but you can see the attitude let me just put aside what I want to do for the moment and let me hear what you want to do ask true love that's open then you can buy and do what you want to do so it's a case of putting yourself in somebody else's shoes and that's when you get this feeling of relating real communication with somebody

295
00:34:25,918 --> 00:34:28,182
Joy being the way of love.

296
00:34:31,108 --> 00:34:41,489
Well joy, as I say, joy arises naturally as another type of relationship of rejoicing.

297
00:34:42,190 --> 00:34:45,818
So you're rejoicing in somebody else's happiness.

298
00:34:46,304 --> 00:35:12,311
and what it undermines the subtle enemy of that is of course envy and jealousy where you want what the other person has jealousy you hate them for having it as well these states they arise naturally you know once you get that basic platform right the one of love

299
00:35:28,728 --> 00:35:33,114
Can you discriminate a bit between skilful desire and unskilful desire?

300
00:35:33,135 --> 00:35:36,239
I thought all desire was to be wary of.

301
00:35:36,460 --> 00:35:37,601
It's the English, really.

302
00:35:38,963 --> 00:35:41,268
The word he's trying to translate is tanha.

303
00:35:41,949 --> 00:35:43,612
This tanha is a specific word.

304
00:35:43,652 --> 00:35:46,416
It means the desire that, it's wrong desire.

305
00:35:46,896 --> 00:35:50,483
It's the desire that arises of seeking happiness in the wrong places.

306
00:35:50,969 --> 00:35:53,291
It's not a skillful desire.

307
00:35:53,512 --> 00:35:58,958
There is another word, candor, which is used to mean both good and bad desires.

308
00:35:59,400 --> 00:36:04,746
So for instance, the desire to sit is a good desire, we should develop that.

309
00:36:05,447 --> 00:36:14,478
And all desires that come from these attitudes that we've been talking about, love, compassion, joy, equanimity, they are to be developed.

310
00:36:15,387 --> 00:36:21,815
What we want to be able to discriminate against are those desires that are coming from misunderstanding.

311
00:36:23,818 --> 00:36:38,458
And to try and do that, you'll see translators translating this tanna as craving, which is, you know, there's no English word really, you'd have to say an unskillful desire, put two words together.

312
00:36:38,878 --> 00:36:39,980
Craving is a bit strong.

313
00:36:41,461 --> 00:36:44,465
So all you have to do is, again, this general awareness,

314
00:36:44,766 --> 00:36:53,398
When you see an intention arise, a desire arise, if you're still, you can see, is this wholesome for me or not?

315
00:36:53,418 --> 00:37:03,751
And then what we have to do is build up enough willpower to resist that temptation, if we see it's not good, and just wait for the, you know, just stay with the agony of letting it go.

316
00:37:05,213 --> 00:37:09,199
And when it goes, you're disempowering it all the time, you're disempowering that condition.

317
00:37:10,340 --> 00:37:12,342
And when we see a desire which is good,

318
00:37:12,525 --> 00:37:19,215
and we want to develop it, every time you practice it, you develop that particular conditioning.

319
00:37:20,117 --> 00:37:20,878
That's how it works.

320
00:37:21,920 --> 00:37:28,730
So, you know, in Buddhist psychology, everything begins with a desire, with an intention.

321
00:37:29,650 --> 00:37:31,934
And these intentions produce actions.

322
00:37:32,916 --> 00:37:35,539
Speech, body, mind, thoughts.

323
00:37:35,679 --> 00:37:36,641
Thoughts are actions.

324
00:37:37,983 --> 00:37:40,726
And through these, we create conditionings, habits.

325
00:37:41,617 --> 00:37:46,922
And the whole compendium, the whole collection of habits that we have is our personality.

326
00:37:47,244 --> 00:37:48,585
That's what the personality is.

327
00:37:49,266 --> 00:37:50,746
Our character, personality.

328
00:37:51,208 --> 00:37:53,309
And it's that which is driving us to a destiny.

329
00:37:54,471 --> 00:38:03,760
So it's becoming aware of those things which are driving us to unfortunate destiny and those which are driving us to happy, happy hunting ground.

330
00:38:04,320 --> 00:38:06,563
So it's a case of discriminating.

331
00:38:06,847 --> 00:38:32,501
for ourselves what's good for us and what's not bad and in this way we change this conditioning this is the way we experience life we're changing the way we experience life any comments?

